%% Drop runs deterministically at end-of-scope — including on panic
%% and on early ? return. There is no Java-style finalizer queue, no
%% Go-style defer statement list, no try-with-resources syntax — the
%% compiler wires it automatically.
sequenceDiagram
    autonumber
    participant Caller
    participant FH as FileHandle
    participant OS as "OS (fd table)"

    Caller->>FH: FileHandle::open("data.txt")
    FH->>OS: open() -> fd
    OS-->>FH: fd = 5
    FH-->>Caller: FileHandle { fd: 5 }

    Caller->>FH: handle.write(bytes)?
    alt write succeeds
        FH-->>Caller: Ok(n)
    else write fails
        FH-->>Caller: Err(IoError)
        Note right of Caller: `?` returns early.<br/>Caller's scope unwinds.
    end

    Note over Caller,FH: end of scope — automatic
    Caller->>FH: drop(handle)
    FH->>OS: close(fd)
    OS-->>FH: ok

    Note right of OS: This sequence runs even on panic!<br/>(unwinding drops stack values in order)
